\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ refers to the twentieth year of King Darius, who is identical with Artaxerxes. In Tractate Rosh 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ Hashanah (3a, b), we find that the phrase ìthe twentieth yearî is mentioned twice using similar 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ wording [to teach us that it is speaking of the identical year]. It states below (2:1), ìAnd it came to 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ pass in the month of Nissan of the twentieth year of Artaxerxes, etc.î The years were calculated from 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ the month of Tishrei. It says here, ìAnd it was in the month of Kislev of the twentieth year, etc.î This 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ refers to the Kislev coming after Tishrei. Further down it says (2:1), ìAnd it was in the month of 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ Nissan of the twentieth year, etc.î This refers to the Nissan of the same year. And I cannot explain 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ that they calculated their years from the month of Nissan and that the incident mentioned below: ìAnd 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ it was in the month of Nissan, etc.î occurred before this incident: ìAnd it was in the month of Kislev, 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ etc.î It is true that events [in the Torah] are not necessarily recorded in chronological order. 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ Nevertheless, the chapters indicate that the second chapter took place only because of the events of 
\lang1033\ltrch\f0\fs36\b0\i0\ul0\cf0\cb8\ the first chapter.  
